      "title": "Minister of Economic Development (2009 - 2019)",
      "depth": 0,
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "Ebrahim Patel was appointed to the Cabinet as Minister of Economic Development in 2009 and was reappointed in 2014."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "His responsibilities include competition and trade policy, industrial funding (of the Industrial Development Corporation (IDC), Africa's largest development finance institution) and infrastructure monitoring and coordination."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "Agencies reporting to his Ministry are: the Competition Commission of South Africa, the Competition Tribunal, the International Trade Administration Commission (ITAC) and IDC."
            },
            {
              "text": "During his time as Minister of Economic Development, he headed the Secretariat of the Presidential Infrastructure Coordinating Commission."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "As Minister of Economic Development, he led the transformation of competition policy in South Africa, with a greater focus by the competition authorities on action against cartels and abuse of dominance."
            },
            {
              "text": "These included action against cartels in the food, construction and auto-component sectors."
            },
            {
              "text": "He introduced a new focus on public interest conditions in mergers and acquisitions, with significant commitments made by companies like Walmart, Coca-Cola, AB InBev and Glencore to retain employment in South Africa, support local industries and small business development, increase investment in production facilities and include South Africans in the equity holdings of their companies."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "Walmart was required by the Competition Appeal Court to establish a R200m Fund to support local small businesses; Coca-Cola agreed with the Ministry to establish an R800 million Fund for local entrepreneurship; and AB InBev agreed to a R1 billion Fund to promote small-scale farmers."
            },
            {
              "text": "Glencore set up a R220 million Fund for small business as part of a settlement with the Ministry."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "His Ministry secured commitments from insurance giant Old Mutual, as part of its return to South Africa, that it would invest R500 million in a Fund to support small business."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sentences": [
            {
              "text": "As part of his oversight of international trade, he focused efforts on driving greater international competitiveness of vulnerable companies through reciprocal commitments by companies who receive trade protection that they will increase investment and innovation."
            },
            {
              "text": "He introduced a trade directive on scrap metal exporters to offer scrap metal to local foundries and steel mini-mills at concessional pricing as part of an effort to support industrialization, lower carbon emission targets in the economy and infrastructure development."
            },
            {
              "text": "His decision was taken on judicial review by two sets of litigants and his Ministry's decision was upheld by the Gauteng North High Court, Western Cape High Court and Supreme Court of Appeal."
